Oct 26 2009 	Decent stay	Accompanied husband on his business trip and stayed at The Radisson Residence on Dubai Marina for 7 nights. Upon check-in, we were kindly upgraded from a studio to a one-bedroom apartment which was really nice for a week-long trip. The room interior is generally modern with 2 LCDs and comfortable sofa and chairs. The room temperature was perfect for a boiling day as well as throughout the night. The kitchen area was handy as we prepared our own breakfast since we figured that the 70 AED hotel breakfast was not worth it. The bathroom was fine, floor always got a little wet and messy though after shower and there wasn't much space around the sink for me to lay my bottles. Internet was complimentary throughout the stay but connection was rather on a slow side. We had mixed feelings about service here. Some staff were extremely friendly and helpful but some other times, we were served by some very cold and pretentious ones. When I asked for directions, they simply said &quot;we don't know&quot; and when I wanted to find out about something, they just gave me a phone to dial myself and said &quot;sorry we're busy&quot;. I found that totally unacceptable and not something I would expect in a hotel of this class. Other than that, I particularly liked the shuttle bus service provided by the hotel so I can hop on and off the malls, although the pick up time wasn't terribly convenient. For a serviced apartment standard, the Radisson certainly lived up to my expectation. Facilities wise, nothing to write home about - tiny pool and gym areas for ladies and there was only one Thai restaurant in a whole building. Marina walk does provide plenty of eateries, so we weren't out of choice. If you want somewhere to stay near the Internet City, Media City, Marina and not fussed about facilities and service, this is a suitable accommodation. However, if you are after a full-scale beach holiday with four or five restaurants and gigantic outdoor pool, this is definitely not a place to book. With an upgrade, we had quite a value for money stay.	
Oct 10 2009 	Unless you are on business - forget it	Large rooms and free Wi-Fi, modern style. TV and DVD. That was the positives.Breakfast in the restaurant is OK, nothing to brag about for 70 AED.All facilities are split genderwise, so forget about sharing time at the pool with your spouse! The female swimmingpool is indoors, so no sunbathing for you girlsNo alcohol available of course. The only restaurant serves Thai food.Good equipment in the fitness center, but if there are more than two people you have to be careful about where you step. The steam and sauna rooms have room for two people each, sitting kne against knee. The hotel is located in the middle of a construction site, with construction ongoing on all sides, even the side facing the motorway. As you can guess this is noisy and dirty. The poolboy has an impossible job keeping the outdoor pool area clean. Internet is free, but slow. The internet provider is also the telecom provider, and has national monopoly it seems, This explains why Skype did not work for me. All in all, the hotel provides somewhere to sleep and work okay. The rest is poor.I did not try the Thai restaurant since I live in Bangkok...The gender split was a no-no for me, I am grateful that I ended up going single. This is the main reason that I can not under any circumstances recommend this hotel. (Poor on service). Location will improve with time, once the construction is completed in a few years.	
Sep 2 2009 	Do not stop at this hotel!	I stopped over at the Radisson Blu recently with my wife, and whilst the hotel was nice enough and the staff friendly, I was informed of a worrying new policy. The pool has been out of action for around two months apparently, but on speaking with one of thre residents I was told that when re-opened the pool and poolside sunbathing area would be OUT OF BOUNDS TO WOMEN! The reason behind this is that, despite being a mixed area prior to refurbishment, the owner has now to decided he wants it to be Shaira complient - even though many Sharia complient hotels in Dubai have no such regulations. Quite how they expect to attract residents or holiday makers to a hotel that doesn't allow families to mix together in the sun is beyond me. Personally, I would not return to the Radisson Blu if you paid me.	
